2xy'y + x^2y' = 0
y'' =\frac{x(-2y') - (-2y)(1)}{x^2} = \frac{-2xy' + 2y}{x^2} = \frac{6y}{x^2}
x^2y = 1 \,\,\,\,\, (\spadesuit)
(\star)
\dfrac{dy}{dx} = - \dfrac{2y}x
(\dagger)
(\spadesuit)
y = \dfrac1{x^2}
y = \dfrac1{x^2}
\dfrac{d(x^2y)}{dx} = 0 \implies \dfrac{d(x^2)}{dx}y + x^2 \dfrac{dy}{dx} = 0\implies 2xy + x^2 \dfrac{dy}{dx} = 0 \implies 2y + x\dfrac{dy}{dx}=0 \,\,\, (\star)
\dfrac{d}{dx} \left(2y + x \dfrac{dy}{dx}\right) = 0 \implies 2 \dfrac{dy}{dx} + \dfrac{d}{dx} \left(x \dfrac{dy}{dx}\right) = 0\\ \implies 2 \dfrac{dy}{dx} + \dfrac{dx}{dx} \dfrac{dy}{dx} + x \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = 0 \implies 3 \dfrac{dy}{dx} + x \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = 0 \,\,\,\, (\dagger)
x \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} + 3 \times \left(- \dfrac{2y}x\right) = 0 \implies \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = \dfrac{6y}{x^2}
\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = \dfrac6{x^4}
\dfrac{dy}{dx} = -\dfrac2{x^3} \implies \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = \dfrac6{x^4}
